Real
Nominal
The [Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations](/Food_and_Agriculture_Organization) (FAO) is a specialized and indispensable [specialized agency](/List_of_specialized_agencies_of_the_United_Nations) operating under the umbrella of the [United Nations](/United_Nations). Its fundamental and ambitious mandate is to spearhead international efforts aimed at eradicating [hunger](/Hunger) and simultaneously enhancing global nutrition and [food security](/Food_security). Its resonant [Latin](/Latin) motto, *fiat panis*, which translates profoundly to "let there be bread," encapsulates its core mission. The organization was officially founded on October 16, 1945, emerging from the ashes of World War II with a clear vision for a food-secure future.

The FAO's extensive membership comprises 195 entities, including 194 individual countries and the powerful [European Union](/European_Union) (EU). Its central headquarters is strategically located in [Rome](/Rome), Italy, but its operational reach is truly global, maintaining a vast network of regional and field offices that span over 130 countries. The organization plays a critical role in assisting both national governments and various development agencies in coordinating their diverse activities. This collaborative effort is geared towards improving and sustainably developing [agriculture](/Agriculture), [forestry](/Forestry) management, [fisheries](/Fishery), and the responsible stewardship of [land](/Land) and [water resources](/Water_resources). Beyond coordination, the FAO actively conducts rigorous research, provides crucial technical assistance for a multitude of projects, operates comprehensive educational and training programs, and meticulously collects and disseminates vital data concerning agricultural output, production trends, and development initiatives worldwide.

The governance structure of the FAO is overseen by a biennial conference, a representative body comprising delegates from each member country and the EU. This conference, in turn, elects a 49-member executive council, which provides ongoing strategic direction. The director-general, a position held by [Qu Dongyu](/Qu_Dongyu) of China as of 2019, serves as the chief administrative officer, responsible for the day-to-day operations and strategic implementation. Various specialized committees are established to govern specific areas, including finance, program development, agriculture, and fisheries, ensuring focused expertise across the organization's broad mandate.

100 [lire](/Italian_lira) (FAO's celebration.)

